# Design lens: biomimicry meets design thinking

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Design Lens is a tool that combines the principles of biomimicry and design thinking to develop innovative solutions.

## Purpose
The purpose of Design Lens is to create impactful solutions that consider both human needs and the needs of the planet.

## How it works
Design Lens helps researchers study natural phenomena to obtain ideas from nature, which are then merged with human-centered design principles to create solutions.

## Requirements
To effectively use Design Lens, designers and innovators need training in both biomimicry and design thinking.

## Reflections
When using Design Lens, it's essential to keep in mind the importance of considering both human needs and environmental sustainability.

## Related methods (if any)
Design Lens is often used in conjunction with other design thinking methods such as brainstorming, co-creation, design sprints, and minimal viable product development.

The license for Design Lens is not specified, but it appears to be a freely available resource.

## Examples
Examples of using Design Lens include the United Nations Development Programme's blog post on "What do fungi, beavers, and elephants have in common? Power to inspire new-age development".
